ecades. In response, Moralities of Drone Violence aims to provide greater clarity by exploring and ordering a variety of ways in which violent drone use can be judged as just or unjust in various circumstances. The book organises moral ideas around a series of concepts of 'drone violence': warfare, violent law enforcement, tele-intimate violence, and violence devolved from humans to artificial intelligence (AI) technologies. In contrast to the way armed drones tend to be debated narrowly in terms of war and law, this broad-based approach to normative inquiry affords more scope to discern and address the potential for these weapon systems to support moral progress or to generate injustice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aPolitics. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023 Englishz978311131914808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023z9783111318226oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107976400 cprintz978147449008540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474490108zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474490108zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474490108/original  a978-3-11-079764-0 Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131914-8 EBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023 Englishb2023  a9